                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote type="drawing" xml:id="d1">
                        <locus target="#1r"/>
                        <desc>Drawing is made with ink, and is partly colored.
                          Emperor <persName ref="PRS7006Menilek">
                          Mǝnilǝk II</persName> riding on the horse,
                          accompanied by servants and soldiers with guns and banners.
                          The caption in the bottom right corner reads
                          <foreign xml:lang="am">ጃንሆይ፡ ያንድ᎓ ቀን᎓ አይን᎓ ነውና᎓ እንዳይነውርብኝ᎓
                          የየካቲት᎓ ጊወርጊስን᎓ ያነገሱለት᎓ አይቼ᎓ ዛሬ᎓ ሰራሁት᎓ </foreign>
                        <foreign xml:lang="en">Your Majesty, this is an impression of one day; may it
                          not become a shame for me.
                          Today I have made (a drawing of) what
                          I saw when you enthroned (the <foreign>tābot</foreign>
                          of) <persName ref="PRS4585Georgeo">George</persName> in <date>Yakkātit</date>.
                        </foreign>
                          </desc>
                        <note>The drawing refers to <persName ref="PRS7006Menilek">
                          Mǝnilǝk II</persName> attending the feast of introducing
                          a <persName ref="PRS4585Georgeo" type="tabot">George of Lydda</persName>
                          into a new church ("enthroning of the tābot"), that probably took place
                          at <placeName ref="LOC3292Gannat">Gannata Ṣǝge Giyorgis</placeName>
                           on the Saint's feast on <date>23 Yakkātit</date>,
                           after 1896 but before 1900. A Russian
                         translation of the legend included into <bibl>
                         <ptr target="bm:Turaev1906rukopisi">
                         </ptr><citedRange unit="page">32</citedRange> was prepared by
                       <persName ref="PRS9149Taklaha">Takla Ḥawāryāt Takla Māryām</persName></bibl>.
                       </note>
                        </decoNote>

